lin could have been completely restored and preserved, or razed in favor of a sanitized, modern city. The reality fell somewhere in between, as decision makers balanced historic preservation against the opportunity to model the Socialist future and reject the example of the Nazi dictatorship through architecture and urban design. Paul Stangl's analysis expands our understanding of urban planning, historic preservation, modernism, and Socialist Realism in East Berlin, shedding light on how the contemporary shape of the city was influenced by ideology and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aArchitecture and statezGermany (East). 0aCity planningzGermanyzBerlinxHistoryy20th century. 0aCommunism and architecturezGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aSocialist realism and architecturezGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 4aBerlin. 4aGerman Democratic Republic. 4aarchitecture. 4acultural politics. 4amemorials. 4amemory. 4aplanning. 4asocialist realism. 4aurban landscape. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503605503zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503605503423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503605503.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles